Ensemble movies with a "star-studded" cast often seem to be name-heavy and story-light. As Benoit Blanc (Daniel Craig's private detective character) says at one point in Knives Out, it is "the exception that proves the rule." Rian Johnson's whodunit has more than a few surprises; it's also a wry take on the privilege of class, the dysfunction of family, the contribution of immigrants, and the decline of personal initiative.  Don't misconstrue: Knives Out is a witty, occasionally laugh-out-loud, cleverly plotted mystery that manages to reinvent the detective story while paying homage to some of the greats: Christie, Chandler, Hammett. Johnson shows a great affinity for the genre, from the memorabilia-crowded rooms of the mansion to the piano key-tickling affectation of Blanc, he sets a tone that incorporates in the noir tale a spitfire humor and a believable premise. The sets, the photography, the writing, the acting, the directing: all contribute to an engaging - pun intended - slice of Hollywood mayhem. It would take too long to single out any one cast member for praise: they inhabit their roles that completely. Knives Out is, to put it mildly, some very sharp cinema.
